{"parse":{"title":"Ways of Seeing","pageid":1281638,"revid":857149779,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p class=\"mw-empty-elt\">\n\n</p>\n<table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><caption style=\"font-style:italic;padding-bottom:0.2em;\">Ways of Seeing <span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Ways+of+Seeing&amp;rft.author=John+Berger&amp;rft.date=1972&amp;rft.pub=Penguin&amp;rft.pages=166&amp;rft_id=info:oclcnum/23135054\"></span></caption><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Waysofseeingcvr.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Waysofseeingcvr.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e3/Waysofseeingcvr.jpg/220px-Waysofseeingcvr.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"341\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/e/e3/Waysofseeingcvr.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"250\" data-file-height=\"388\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Author</th><td>\nJohn Berger</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Cover&#160;artist</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Magritte\" title=\"Ren\u00e9 Magritte\">Ren\u00e9 Magritte</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Country</th><td>\nU.K.</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Language</th><td>\nEnglish</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Subject</th><td>\nArt, architecture, photography</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Publisher</th><td>\nPenguin</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><div style=\"padding:0.1em 0;line-height:1.2em;\">Publication date</div></th><td>\n1972</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Pages</th><td>\n166</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a></th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-14-013515-4\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-14-013515-4\">0-14-013515-4</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/OCLC#Identifiers_and_linked_data\" title=\"OCLC\"><abbr title=\"Online Computer Library Center number\">OCLC</abbr></a></th><td>\n<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/23135054\">23135054</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>Ways of Seeing</b></i> is a 1972 television series of 30-minute films created chiefly by writer <a href=\"/wiki/John_Berger\" title=\"John Berger\">John Berger</a> and producer <a href=\"/wiki/Mike_Dibb\" title=\"Mike Dibb\">Mike Dibb</a>. It was broadcast on <a href=\"/wiki/BBC_Two\" title=\"BBC Two\">BBC Two</a> in January 1972 and adapted into a book of the same name. \n</p><p>The series was intended as a response to <a href=\"/wiki/Kenneth_Clark\" title=\"Kenneth Clark\">Kenneth Clark</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Civilisation_(TV_series)\" title=\"Civilisation (TV series)\">Civilisation</a></i> series, which represents a more traditionalist view of the Western artistic and cultural canon, and the series and book criticize traditional <a href=\"/wiki/Western_culture\" title=\"Western culture\">Western cultural</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Aesthetics\" title=\"Aesthetics\">aesthetics</a> by raising questions about hidden <a href=\"/wiki/Ideology\" title=\"Ideology\">ideologies</a> in visual images. \n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Episodes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Episodes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Book\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Book</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Episodes\">Episodes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ways_of_Seeing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Episodes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<table class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders wikiepisodetable\" style=\"width:%\"><tbody><tr style=\"color:black;text-align:center\"><th scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#CCCCFF;width:5%\"><abbr title=\"Number\">No.</abbr> in<br />series</th><th scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#CCCCFF\">Title</th><th scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#CCCCFF\">Original air date</th></tr><tr class=\"vevent\" style=\"text-align:center;background:#F2F2F2\"><th scope=\"row\" id=\"ep1\" style=\"text-align:center\">1</th><td class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:left\">\"Episode 1\"</td><td>8&#160;January&#160;1972<span style=\"display:none\">&#160;(<span class=\"bday dtstart published updated\">1972-01-08</span>)</span></td></tr><tr><td class=\"description\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-bottom:solid 3px #CCCCFF\">\nThe first part of the television series drew on ideas from <a href=\"/wiki/Walter_Benjamin\" title=\"Walter Benjamin\">Walter Benjamin</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Work_of_Art_in_the_Age_of_Mechanical_Reproduction\" title=\"The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction\">The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction</a></i> arguing that through reproduction an <a href=\"/wiki/Old_Master\" title=\"Old Master\">Old Master</a>'s painting's modern context is severed from that which existed at the time of its making.<sup id=\"cite_ref-auto_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-auto-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></td></tr>\n<tr class=\"vevent\" style=\"text-align:center;background:#F2F2F2\"><th scope=\"row\" id=\"ep2\" style=\"text-align:center\">2</th><td class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:left\">\"Episode 2\"</td><td>15&#160;January&#160;1972<span style=\"display:none\">&#160;(<span class=\"bday dtstart published updated\">1972-01-15</span>)</span></td></tr><tr><td class=\"description\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-bottom:solid 3px #CCCCFF\">\nThe second film discusses the female <a href=\"/wiki/Depictions_of_nudity\" title=\"Depictions of nudity\">nude</a>. Berger asserts that only twenty or thirty nudes in the European oil painting tradition depict a woman as herself rather than as a subject of male idealisation or desire.<sup id=\"cite_ref-auto_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-auto-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></td></tr>\n<tr class=\"vevent\" style=\"text-align:center;background:#F2F2F2\"><th scope=\"row\" id=\"ep3\" style=\"text-align:center\">3</th><td class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:left\">\"Episode 3\"</td><td>22&#160;January&#160;1972<span style=\"display:none\">&#160;(<span class=\"bday dtstart published updated\">1972-01-22</span>)</span></td></tr><tr><td class=\"description\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-bottom:solid 3px #CCCCFF\">\nThe third programme is on the use of <a href=\"/wiki/Oil_paint\" title=\"Oil paint\">oil paint</a> as a means of depicting or reflecting the <a href=\"/wiki/Social_status\" title=\"Social status\">status</a> of the individuals who commissioned the work of art.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></td></tr>\n<tr class=\"vevent\" style=\"text-align:center;background:#F2F2F2\"><th scope=\"row\" id=\"ep4\" style=\"text-align:center\">4</th><td class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:left\">\"Episode 4\"</td><td>29&#160;January&#160;1972<span style=\"display:none\">&#160;(<span class=\"bday dtstart published updated\">1972-01-29</span>)</span></td></tr><tr><td class=\"description\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-bottom:solid 3px #CCCCFF\">\nIn the fourth programme, on publicity and advertising, Berger argues that colour <a href=\"/wiki/Photography\" title=\"Photography\">photography</a> has taken over the role of oil paint, though the context is reversed. An idealised potential for the viewer (via <a href=\"/wiki/Consumerism\" title=\"Consumerism\">consumption</a>) is considered a substitution for the actual <a href=\"/wiki/Reality\" title=\"Reality\">reality</a> depicted in old master portraits.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Book\">Book</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ways_of_Seeing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Book\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The book <i>Ways of Seeing</i> was written by Berger and Dibb, along with Sven Blomberg, Chris Fox, and <a href=\"/wiki/Richard_Hollis\" title=\"Richard Hollis\">Richard Hollis</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ways_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ways-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The book consists of seven numbered <a href=\"/wiki/Essay\" title=\"Essay\">essays</a>: four using words and images; and three essays using only images.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ways_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ways-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The book has contributed to <a href=\"/wiki/Feminism\" title=\"Feminism\">feminist</a> readings of <a href=\"/wiki/Popular_culture\" title=\"Popular culture\">popular culture</a>, through essays that focus particularly on how women are portrayed in advertisements and oil paintings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> \"Berger, who died on 2 January 2017 at the age of 90, has had a profound influence on the popular understanding of art and the visual image,\" according to sociologists Yasmin Gunaratnam and Vikki Bell.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ways_of_Seeing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation journal\">Bruck, Jan; Docker, John (1989). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://wwwmcc.murdoch.edu.au/ReadingRoom/2.2/Bruck.html\">\"Puritanic Relationalism: John Berger's Ways of Seeing and Media and Culture Studies\"</a>. <i>Continuum: The Australian Journal of Media &amp; Culture</i>. <b>2</b> (2): 77\u201395<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2016-04-22</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Continuum%3A+The+Australian+Journal+of+Media+%26+Culture&amp;rft.atitle=Puritanic+Relationalism%3A+John+Berger%27s+Ways+of+Seeing+and+Media+and+Culture+Studies&amp;rft.volume=2&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=77-95&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.aulast=Bruck&amp;rft.aufirst=Jan&amp;rft.au=Docker%2C+John&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwwwmcc.murdoch.edu.au%2FReadingRoom%2F2.2%2FBruck.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AWays+of+Seeing\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation web\">Chandler, Daniel (30 June 1998). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://visual-memory.co.uk/daniel/Documents/gaze/\">\"Notes on 'The Gaze': John Berger's <i>Ways of Seeing</i>\"</a>. Aberystwyth: University of Wales<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2016-04-22</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Notes+on+%27The+Gaze%27%3A+John+Berger%27s+Ways+of+Seeing&amp;rft.place=Aberystwyth&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Wales&amp;rft.date=1998-06-30&amp;rft.aulast=Chandler&amp;rft.aufirst=Daniel&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fvisual-memory.co.uk%2Fdaniel%2FDocuments%2Fgaze%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AWays+of+Seeing\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation web\">Dillon, George (October 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://courses.washington.edu/englhtml/engl569/berger/\">\"Illustrations and Amplifications for John Berger's Ways of Seeing\"</a>. Seattle: University of Washington<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2016-04-22</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Illustrations+and+Amplifications+for+John+Berger%27s+Ways+of+Seeing&amp;rft.place=Seattle&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Washington&amp;rft.date=2013-10&amp;rft.aulast=Dillon&amp;rft.aufirst=George&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcourses.washington.edu%2Fenglhtml%2Fengl569%2Fberger%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AWays+of+Seeing\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation web\">Saxton Acker, John (ed.). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://jan.ucc.nau.edu/~jsa3/hum355/readings/berger.htm\">\"John Berger &#91;An extended quotation from an episode of <i>Ways of Seeing</i>&#93;\"</a>. Flagstaff: Northern Arizona University<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2016-04-22</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=John+Berger+%5BAn+extended+quotation+from+an+episode+of+Ways+of+Seeing%5D&amp;rft.place=Flagstaff&amp;rft.pub=Northern+Arizona+University&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fjan.ucc.nau.edu%2F~jsa3%2Fhum355%2Freadings%2Fberger.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AWays+of+Seeing\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ways_of_Seeing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-auto-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-auto_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-auto_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/d73c951a08e04d21a5f6c3f4dd2ec08b\">Radio Times</a>, Genome Project</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/93ac9d4e398441a4874c1af860a3acdc\">Radio Times</a>, Genome Project</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/81cf6b977885418cb2857b6de8fe32d6\">Radio Times</a>, Genome Project</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Ways-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Ways_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b